## Legal Status — READ BEFORE BUILDING ANY REVENUE FEATURES
Last updated: April 3, 2026
Source: Two rounds of ChatGPT deep research into NJ real estate law

### IMMEDIATE ACTIONS REQUIRED

1. STOP COMMISSION SPLIT WITH AGENT FRIEND — IMMEDIATELY
The current arrangement where the licensed agent splits their commission
with Dev (unlicensed) is a direct violation of N.J.S.A. 45:15-17(k).
This puts the agent's real estate LICENSE at risk — not just Dev.
The 2024 NJ Real Estate Commission disciplinary actions show the Commission
is actively sanctioning agents for exactly this type of arrangement.
Action: Agent keeps 100% of their commission through their broker.
HouseRush invoices landlords SEPARATELY for platform/advertising fees only.
The two revenue streams must never touch.

2. NEVER INVOICE LANDLORDS BASED ON LEASE OUTCOMES UNTIL LICENSED
Per N.J.S.A. 45:15 and confirmed by two rounds of legal research, the
moment HouseRush charges a fee because a lease closed, HouseRush needs
a NJ real estate broker license or licensed brokerage subsidiary.
This includes: success fees, per-lease fees, commission percentages,
referral fees tied to completed leases.
DO NOT BUILD pay-per-lease invoicing until licensed entity is formed.

### WHAT IS SAFE TO CHARGE RIGHT NOW

HouseRush can charge landlords flat advertising/software fees only:
- $150/month featured listing badge — SAFE (pure advertising)
- $199/month platform subscription — SAFE (software access)
- $500 flat listing placement fee — SAFE (one-time advertising)

These fees must be:
- Flat rate (not percentage of rent or commission)
- Not described as commission split, referral fee, or success fee
- Invoiced directly by HouseRush to the landlord
- Completely separate from any commission the agent earns

### THE COMPLIANT STRUCTURE RIGHT NOW

Two completely separate transactions:

TRANSACTION 1 (agent's money):
Landlord → pays commission → agent's broker → agent keeps 100%
HouseRush never touches this money. Ever.

TRANSACTION 2 (HouseRush's money):
Landlord → pays flat marketing/software fee → HouseRush directly
This is advertising revenue. Not brokerage compensation.

### LANDLORD AGREEMENT LANGUAGE (USE THIS TEMPLATE)
Every landlord on the platform should eventually sign an agreement stating:
- HouseRush is not a real estate broker, agent, or property manager
- HouseRush does not negotiate, show, screen, select, or recommend tenants
- HouseRush provides only advertising, lead delivery, listing software,
  and platform services
- Any fee paid to HouseRush is consideration for software and marketing
  only, not for leasing activity
- Landlord retains sole authority for: communicating with prospects,
  showing the property, screening applicants, negotiating and executing
  leases, accepting or rejecting any applicant
- Landlord independently evaluated and selected the tenant
- Landlord may choose not to use any lead received through HouseRush

### FEATURES THAT CREATE LEGAL EXPOSURE IF MONETIZED
The following features are fine as FREE product features but cannot have
transaction-based fees attached until HouseRush is licensed:
- Auction format and winner selection (looks like procuring prospects)
- Bid recommendation engine (looks like recommending one applicant)
- Auto-bid system (looks like negotiating on tenant's behalf)
- Secure Lease Now (platform facilitating lease bypass)
- Group Bidding winner selection (platform selecting which group wins)
- Competition scoring between tenants (match scoring = brokerage)

These features are your product differentiators. KEEP THEM.
Just do not attach per-lease success fees to their outcomes until licensed.

### WHAT THE AUCTION LEGALLY NEEDS TO LOOK LIKE
For the advertising model to hold up under NJ law, the platform must
appear to function as:
- HouseRush hosts a listing page
- All applicants/bidders are transmitted to the landlord
- Landlord alone chooses who to lease to
- HouseRush does not curate, rank, or influence the final outcome
- Landlord could ignore the auction winner entirely if they chose to

The auction is a UX feature that helps landlords see student interest.
It is NOT HouseRush selecting or placing a tenant.

### PORTABLE APPLICATION — REVISED STRUCTURE
Original plan (ILLEGAL): Charge students $25-30 before lease execution
for help locating housing. Criminal exposure under N.J.S.A. 45:15-1.2.

Revised plan (SAFE): Charge students a flat post-lease move-in package
fee AFTER lease is signed. Content:
- Archived application storage
- Moving concierge connections
- Renters insurance comparison
- Utilities setup assistance
- Rent payment setup
A flat fee after lease execution is outside the criminal statute entirely.
DO NOT charge this fee before the lease is signed.

### THE LICENSED BROKERAGE ENTITY ROADMAP
When HouseRush is ready for pay-per-lease revenue, it needs:
- A New Jersey licensed brokerage entity (subsidiary or partner)
- A licensed NJ broker of record
- All pay-per-lease revenue flowing through that brokerage
- The auction/selection process legally owned by the licensed entity

This is a Month 4-6 project requiring a NJ real estate attorney.
Estimated attorney consultation cost: $300-500 for initial structure.

Timeline:
NOW: Featured badge $150/month only. Agent keeps 100% commission.
Month 2-3: Consult NJ attorney re: licensed brokerage subsidiary.
Month 4-6: Form licensed NJ brokerage entity with broker of record.
Month 6+: Pay-per-lease billing launches through licensed entity.
Year 2+: Full revenue model at scale across multiple campuses.

### WHAT TO TELL THE AGENT FRIEND
"I did legal research and the commission split we have been doing could
put your license at risk under N.J.S.A. 45:15-17(k). I don't want to
do that to you. From now on you keep 100% of your commission. I will
invoice landlords separately for the platform fee. Our partnership still
makes sense — you bring listings, I bring students, you earn your full
commission, I earn my advertising fee. Nobody's license is at risk."

### PENALTIES FOR GETTING THIS WRONG
- Agent: fines, license suspension, probation, possible revocation
- HouseRush: up to $5,000 first violation, up to $10,000 each subsequent
  violation, each transaction treated as a separate offense
- Criminal exposure (portable app fee before lease): minimum $200 fine,
  up to 30 days imprisonment under N.J.S.A. 45:15-1.2
- Jeffrey Ray precedent: $10,000 fine, restitution, cease-and-desist

### NATIONAL EXPANSION NOTE
NJ is one of the strictest states. Once licensed brokerage entity is
formed in NJ, research each new state before launching:
- Texas: apartment locating treated as licensed brokerage activity
- New York: strict commission splitting prohibitions, misdemeanor violations
- California: broad broker definition covers leasing/renting for compensation
- Each state requires individual legal review before pay-per-lease launches

## Claude API Integration Plan (Decided April 2026)

ANTHROPIC_API_KEY goes in Railway environment variables.
All Claude integration lives in /server/src/lib/claude.ts

Build order:

1. Fair Housing Listing Linter (FIRST — build this week/next 30 days)
   - Model: Haiku 4.5 (fast, cheap)
   - Cost: ~$0.02 per listing
   - Fires at listing submission, before admin approval queue
   - Flags potentially discriminatory language, suggests neutral rewrites,
     logs changes
   - Protects HouseRush legally as platform operator
   - This is safe to build regardless of legal status above

2. Fraud Check on New Signups
   - Model: Haiku 4.5
   - Cost: ~$0.01 per signup
   - Combines weak signals into risk narrative with reason codes
   - Extends existing .edu email verification

3. Lease Verification MVP (build the feature, hold the billing trigger)
   - Model: Sonnet 4.6 via Claude Agent SDK (not raw API)
   - Cost: ~$0.05 per lease
   - Student uploads signed lease PDF after auction closes
   - Claude extracts: parties, address, rent, dates, signatures present,
     anomaly flags
   - Returns guaranteed valid JSON via structured outputs
   - BUILD the verification feature now for trust/transparency
   - DO NOT trigger pay-per-lease invoice until legal structure is resolved
   - Use TWO-AGENT PATTERN: read-only reader agent processes untrusted PDF,
     separate actor agent triggers billing. Never let untrusted content
     directly trigger billing.

Raw API vs Agent SDK:
- Raw API = single question, single answer. Use for linter and fraud check.
- Agent SDK = autonomous reasoning loop, multi-step. Use for lease
  verification.
- Both use the same package: npm install @anthropic-ai/sdk
- API key obtained from console.anthropic.com, stored in Railway env vars

## Three-Layer Storage Architecture (To Build Toward)

1. Turso core DB — structured data only. IDs, bid amounts, timestamps,
   normalized lease fields, reason codes. Never raw documents.
2. Document vault — encrypted storage for lease PDFs, student ID photos,
   enrollment proof. Separate from main DB. Time-to-live on all raw
   artifacts. Access logged.
3. Model I/O logs — minimal Claude audit trail. What was sent, what came
   back, confidence score, timestamp.

